userStories.notes:
The fix is in docs/components/MDX.tsx, the code component override (currently lines 82-90).

Current code:
  code: ({ className, children, ...props }: React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLElement>) => (
    <code
      className={cn(
        'bg-inline-code-bg text-inline-code-fg border-border/30 relative rounded-(--radius) border px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-sm',
        className,
      )}
      {...props}>
      {children}
    </code>
  ),

The problem: this applies inline-code styling to ALL <code> elements, including <code> inside <pre> for language-less blocks. For language-less code blocks, the MDX render pipeline is:
  1. <pre> → CodeBlock component (applies bg-code-bg text-code-fg p-4)
  2. <code> inside <pre> → this code override (applies bg-inline-code-bg border px-1.5 py-0.5)
The inner <code> gets conflicting styling — different background, a border, and padding that pushes content inward.

For rehype-pretty-code-processed blocks (with a language), the <code> gets data-language, data-theme, and inline style attributes from Shiki that override the Tailwind classes. So those blocks look fine despite the override.

For language-less blocks, there's no Shiki override, so the inline-code styles are fully visible and cause the visual bug.

Fix approach — detect block context and skip inline styling:

  code: ({ className, children, ...props }: React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLElement>) => {
    // Skip inline-code styling for code elements inside code blocks.
    // Block code is identified by: (1) data-language/data-theme from rehype-pretty-code,
    // or (2) children containing newlines (language-less code blocks).
    const isBlock =
      'data-language' in props ||
      'data-theme' in props ||
      (typeof children === 'string' && children.includes('\n'));

    if (isBlock) {
      return (
        <code className={className} {...props}>
          {children}
        </code>
      );
    }

    return (
      <code
        className={cn(
          'bg-inline-code-bg text-inline-code-fg border-border/30 relative rounded-(--radius) border px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-sm',
          className,
        )}
        {...props}>
        {children}
      </code>
    );
  },

The 'in props' check works because the ...props rest object contains all HTML attributes not destructured. data-language and data-theme are set by rehype-pretty-code on block code elements.

The typeof children === 'string' && children.includes('\n') check works because language-less block <code> children are template literal strings with newlines (verified via build output), while inline <code> children are plain strings without newlines.

IMPORTANT: The component currently uses an arrow function with implicit return (parenthesized JSX). The fix requires conditional logic, so it must be converted to a block body with explicit returns. Make sure the TypeScript types are correct — the component signature stays the same.
